Amsterdam mourned the tragic death of filmmaker Theo van Gogh, known for his controversial views on Islam.
A memorial gathering was held in Dam square, with two minutes of silence observed in his memory.
Van Gogh's collaboration with Ayaan Hirsi Ali, a vocal critic of women's treatment in Islamic culture, led to his untimely demise.
The Dutch Muslim community condemned the murder, emphasizing the importance of freedom of speech.
The suspect, with ties to Islamic extremists, sparked a national debate on tolerance and division in Dutch society.
Van Gogh's legacy as a provocative artist continues to resonate despite his tragic end.
